\par This document is Open Game Content, as described in section 1(d) of the License.}{\insrsid8009706   The license is found at the end of this document.}{\insrsid6771226 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs48\insrsid6771226 1. Introduction
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Fate is a story-oriented roleplayi
ng game system. Though it is a full-fledged standalone system, Fate can also be incorporated into a variety of popular roleplaying systems. In this book, we present a version of Fate that has been tailored to work with Fudge, an RPG by Steffan O'Sullivan.
 
As such, we assume the reader is familiar with Fudge, and while everything necessary to play is included, you are strongly encouraged to acquire a copy of Fudge, either at your local game store, or for free online at fudgerpg.com. Those interested in star
ting out immediately may wish to check out \'d2Simple Fudge\'d3.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 1.1 The Adjectives
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 
The most important thing to understand about Fudge is how it describes things. Rather than assigning numerical values to elements like skills it uses adjectives, which are ranked as follows: Abysmal, Terrible, Poor, Mediocre, Average, Fair, Good, Great, S
uperb, Epic, and Legendary. Consider: a bodyguard might be a Good swordsman but have Mediocre social skills. He\rquote ll probably win a fight with an artist who\rquote 
s a Superb painter but a Poor swordsman. Almost anything can be described using this ladder \emdash  an empire may field a Superb army or a spaceship may be limping by with a Poor engine.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 1.2 Rolling the Dice
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 To roll dice for Fate, pick your starting level (say, Good) and roll four six-sided dice. For each 1 or 2, move down one step, and for each 5 or 6 move up one. }{
\insrsid5639858 Let\rquote s}{\insrsid6771226 
 say we rolled 2,3,5 and 5. Go down a step because of the 2, from Good to Fair, but then go up a step thanks to the first 5 (from Fair to Good) and again from the second 5 (from Good to Great) for a final outcome of Great.
\par Another way to look at the dice is as if they rolled either +1, 0 or -1. From that perspective, rolling 2,3,5,5 is the same as rolling -1,0,+1,+1, which is easier to deal with, since that just becomes Good + 1, which is Great. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 Visualize it like this:
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 The Ladder
\par Value\tab \tab Descriptor
\par +6\tab \tab Legendary
\par +5\tab \tab Epic
\par +4\tab \tab Superb
\par +3\tab \tab Great
\par +2\tab \tab Good
\par +1\tab \tab Fair
\par 0\tab \tab Average
\par -1\tab \tab Mediocre
\par -2\tab \tab Poor
\par -3\tab \tab Terrible
\par -4\tab \tab Abysmal
\par There are special dice available for Fudge that have plus (+), minus(-) and blank(0) faces to make rolling easier, and we use them to clarify examples. These dice can be purchased at many game stores, or online through Grey Ghost Press (www.fudgerpg.com).

\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 1.3 Success and Failure
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 When the dice are rolled, there is usually a target difficulty described according to the ladder. For instance,
 it might take a Good climbing effort to ascend a steep wall. To face this challenge, the player consults the appropriate skill, rolls the dice, and compares the outcome to the difficulty. If the outcome is equal to or higher than the difficulty, it's a s
uccess; if not, it's a failure. The difference between the difficulty and the outcome is called the margin of success (or failure), MoS or MoF respectively. It is often used to determine how well the character succeeded or how badly they failed.
\par When two ch
aracters are competing in a task, they both roll; the difference between the outcomes is the MoS for the winner and the MoF for the loser. A check made against a static target is a Test, while one made against another character is a Challenge. There are a
 couple of rules (see \'d2Tests and Challenges\'d3) for handling more complicated circumstances, but most of the time, this is really all there is to it.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs48\insrsid6771226 2. Character Creation
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Character creation is, ideally, very interactive, with the entire group crea
ting characters in the presence of the GM. The methods below can be adapted to a less group-focused approach, but doing so loses many of benefits of the Fate approach. Character creation consists of a small number of simple steps.
\par 1. GM Overview.
\par 2. Consider the character.
\par 3. Describe each phase
\par 4. Select the Aspects for the phase
\par 5. Spend 4 Skill Ranks
\par 6. Assign Fate points.
\par 7. Select character goal.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 2.1 GM Overview
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Character generat
ion should begin with the GM talking to the players about the game, in order to set appropriate expectations. The GM should address any rules considerations, such as how many phases there will be (see below). More importantly, she should make sure that ev
e
ryone gets a clear idea of the theme and tone of the game. If all of the players want a game of courtly intrigue and the GM is planning to run a hack and slash adventure, this is a good time to find that out. Finally, the GM should give the players whatev
er background information they need to know.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 2.2 Consider Characters
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 
It's often helpful for players to get a sense of the sort of character they'd like to play. A lot of things can happen during the phases, so it's easiest to start with a simple idea, and b
uild on it over the course of character generation. Once everyone has a concept, players should feel free to discuss them, unless the GM says otherwise. No player is obliged to participate in the discussion. In fact, no player is even obliged to have an i
dea at this point. However, doing so allows players to get a sense of what direction their fellow players want to take things, and it gives the GM a sense of what the group dynamic might look like.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 2.3 Phases
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Creation will have a number of phases set by the
 GM. Most games will use between five and eight, but it can really be any number. A phase is defined as a period of time wherein some events of note took place, but the specifics vary from game to game. A game of high school monster hunters might consider
 
each school year a phase, while a game of immortal swordsmen might have a phase for every 50 years. Whatever the duration, the GM gives the players a sense of what was going on at the time, and the players figure out what their character was doing at the 
time. 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 2.4 Select Aspects
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Players pick one or more aspects to represent important elements of the character that can tie into the events of the phase.
\par Aspects are used to describe any element of the character. Aspects include things like attributes (Strong,
 Weak, Agile, Charismatic, Tough, Fast, Slow), descriptors (Dutiful Charming, Alert, Dramatic), careers (Knight, Mercenary, Musketeer, Cutthroat) or even ties to the setting (Merry Man of Sherwood, Initiate of the Blue Wind, Fiodario Fencing Academy). Asp
ects may be good, bad or both but they should always reflect some important element of the character.
\par When an aspect is chosen the character gains one level of that aspect, noted as follows:
\par \tab [] Knight (Fair)
\par An aspect may be chosen again on a subsequent phase, in which case it goes up a level and is noted as:
\par \tab [][] Knight (Good)
\par And then
\par \tab [][][] Knight (Great)
\par The GM sets the maximum number of levels that can be chosen in a given aspect, but a good rule of thumb is a third to a half of the total number of phases.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 2.5 Skill Ranks
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Skill ranks, as the name suggests, are spent primarily to purchase skills, but they can also be invested in resources.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 2.5.1 Buying Skills
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Skill ranks may be spent to buy new skills or to improve existing ones. Acquiring a new skill 
costs one skill rank, and sets the skill at Average. Spending a skill rank to improve a skill raises it one step per rank spent (from Fair to Good, for example, or Superb to Epic.).  Skills will generally be selected from a skill list (see \'d2Skill Lists
\'d3.)
\par Once the aspects are chosen, the player then picks four skill ranks appropriate to the events of the phase. If the player had spent the phase training in an order of knights, then skills like swords, riding or heraldry would probably be appropri
ate, while skills like }{\insrsid5639858 garrote}{\insrsid6771226  or needlework would not (barring a very odd order of knighthood).
\par Skills are described according to the adjective ladder, and default to Mediocre. Spending one skill rank increases a skill to Average, spending a second incre
ases it to Fair, spending another increases it to Good and so on. Players may spend those four skill ranks any way they like with only one limitation: there must always be one more skill in the next rank down. This means that a character must have two ski
lls at Fair to have a skill at Good (and must have three skills at Average to have the two skills at Fair!). Because of how this looks, it is referred to as the skill pyramid. When the rules are observed, the pyramid is considered to be \'d2balanced.\'d3
 The pyramid must be balanced at the end of every phase. This process is repeated for each phase.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 2.5.2 Looking at the Pyramid
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 The pyramid can get confusing the first time you try to keep track of it. The good news is it\rquote s the hardest part of the system - once you\rquote 
re past that, the rest is easy.
\par It\rquote s often helpful to use }{\insrsid5639858 tick marks}{\insrsid6771226  to track progression through the phases, since it allows a visual representation of the pyramid.
\par Looking at the sample character later on (see \'d2Sample Creation\'d3) in the first phase, the character buys ranks in knife, Herb Lore, Healing, Alertness. This can be marked as:
\par Knife\tab \tab \tab X
\par Herb Lore\tab \tab X
\par Healing\tab \tab X
\par Alertness\tab \tab X
\par Next phase, she buys ranks of Knife, Healing, Bluff and Pickpocket:
\par Knife\tab \tab \tab XX
\par Herb Lore\tab \tab X
\par Healing\tab \tab XX
\par Alertness\tab \tab X
\par Bluff\tab \tab \tab X
\par Pickpocket\tab \tab X
\par And next, Knife, Bluff, Alertness and Move Silently:
\par Knife\tab \tab \tab XXX
\par Herb Lore\tab \tab X
\par Healing\tab \tab XX
\par Alertness\tab \tab XX
\par Bluff\tab \tab \tab XX
\par Pickpocket\tab \tab X
\par Move Silently\tab \tab X
\par And the marks show the problem. There are 3 XX and 3 X - that\rquote s unbalanced.    Instead of Bluff, she picks Hide instead, so:
\par Knife\tab \tab \tab XXX
\par Herb Lore\tab \tab X
\par Healing\tab \tab XX
\par Alertness\tab \tab XX
\par Bluff\tab \tab \tab X
\par Pickpocket\tab \tab X
\par Move Silently\tab \tab X
\par Hide\tab \tab \tab X
\par This system saves the trouble of assigning adjectives at each level. Instead, whenever you\rquote re finished, simply count up the marks, and assign a value as follows:
\par \tab 1\tab Average
\par \tab 2\tab Fair
\par \tab 3\tab Good
\par \tab 4\tab Great
\par \tab 5\tab Superb
\par \tab 6\tab Epic
\par \tab 7\tab Legendary
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 2.5.3 Why does Basketweaving help my Swordplay?
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 
\par During character creation and, later, advancement (which is, in the end, the same as character creation in slow motion), you may find yourself wanting to bump a key skill up another level, but lacking the supporting pyramid structure to make that happen.

\par Of course, the thing to do at this point is to expand the base of the pyramid first, by adding other skills, in order to provide the structure to support the eventual higher skill.
\par This is all well and good as a mechanic for keeping skills from rising too fast, but you might be asking, \'d2What's the justification?\'d3 Some of tho
se skills you're adding at the lower levels might not seem like they'd have anything to do with the skill you're \'d2really\'d3 trying to promote.
\par Part of the \'d2in game\'d3 idea of what's going on here is that, with the troublesome \'d2peak\'d3 skill in question, you've p
lateaued. Perhaps you've gotten about as good as you can get for a while, and it's time to branch out a bit, shake yourself up a little, and then come back refreshed with new perspectives.
\par Another possibility is that you *are* still improving in that skill
, even if its listed rank isn't changing. Consider: the grain of the adjective ladder in Fate is pretty rough, with each rung of the ladder representing a significant step beyond the one prior to it. So while you may be improving, you're not improving so 
significantly that you've jumped up another level -- yet. The fact that you're picking up other skills along the way indicates that time is passing, which is the \'d2true\'d3 support that's being lent to your peak skill.
\par That all said, in theory, your skill choic
es within a phase (be it a period of advancement leading up to a goal aspect, or a phase during character creation) are related to the aspect you're getting during that phase, so chances are the skills you're picking up are going to be a bit more related 
to your Swordplay than, say, Basketweaving.
\par Say the skill in question is Swordplay. There are any number of things you could pick up that clearly do support that skill. For example:
\par Metalworking (make your own)
\par Knowledge: Fencing Schools
\par Shield Use
\par Athletics
\par Alertness
\par Other weapon skills
\par A skill to represent an advanced maneuver that isn't covered by your Swordplay skill
\par And so on. Knowledge and profession skills are often great picks during these times, as they expand the realm of things your character knows about, while still tying into the peak skill you're pushing.
\par That said, if you're learning Swordplay under the Great Kenjutsu 
Master Hiroko, and he sends you down to the river to make baskets out of reeds every day as a part of your training in discipline and patience -- there's always justification to take Basketweaving.
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 2.6 Fate Points
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Fate points are points which may be spent
 by a player to grant a bonus to an action or to influence the game in some way. The GM gives each player a certain number of them at the game\rquote s start, usually equal to half the number of phases. See \'d2Fate Points\'d3 for more details.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 2.7 Select Character Goal
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 
Finally, the player should pick what direction they want the character to go in next. This is expressed as a goal, which should be the next aspect the player would like for the character. It\rquote s possible that the player will not have an idea, an
d that\rquote s fine, but the goals help tell the GM the sorts of things the players are interested in. See \'d2Advancement\'d3 for more information.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 2.8 Sample Creation
\par }{\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 2.8.1 GM Overview
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 The GM explains that the game is going to be a standard fantasy game with a slightly urban and low magic flavor, and that character generation will be five phases.
\par Think about and discuss the character
\par Deborah decides to make Sybil, who she thinks is going to be something of a trickster, but she hasn\rquote t got much more than that.
