\par 
\par Armor\rquote s protection is generally limited to preventing wounds. As such, it does not change th
e difficulty of maneuvers. When fighting someone in plate mail, it is easier to disarm them, a hurt outcome equivalent (AL 0, 2-4) than it is to actually hurt them (AT 3, 4-5).  
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\insrsid6771226 8.4.3 Weapons
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 It is possible to have an even finer grain of difference between weapons by assigning specific attributes to them. For example:
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Armor Piercing (AP)}{\insrsid6771226  - Armor Piercing weapons reduce armor rating by 2, but are -1 to use. Extremely potent armor piercing weapons (APx2) reduce armor rating by 4, but suffer a -2 penalty.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Flexible (Flex)}{\insrsid6771226  - Flexible weapons grant a +1 to maneuvers like disarms, but provide a -1 penalty in any fight where both parties have reasonable mobility.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Vicious (Vcs)}{\insrsid6771226  - Vicious weapons are designed to rip and tear flesh, and increase their damage by 1 poin
ts. However, any armor greater than 0 is considered 2 levels higher against the attack. Vcsx2 weapons increase damage by 2 but improves existing armor by 4.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Locking (Lock)}{\insrsid6771226  - Weapon locks to the user\rquote s gauntlet (or is part of it). As such, the weapon cannot be disarmed, but it also takes a -1 penalty to any maneuvers requiring finesse.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\insrsid6771226 8.4.4 Other Combat Modifiers
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 A number of other elements can affect the direction of a fight, including:
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Superior Position}{\insrsid6771226  - this is something of a catch-all to cover situational modifiers. Possible reasons for receiving this modifier include:
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Elevated position}{\insrsid6771226 
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Cover}{\insrsid6771226 
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Fighting from horseback}{\insrsid6771226 
\par In general, these situations shouldn\rquote t provide more than a +1 bonus, save in the most egregious of circumstances. 
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Outnumbering}{\insrsid6771226  - +1 bonus for outnumbering your opponent.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Flanking}{\insrsid6771226  - +1 bonus for getting in a position where your opponent\rquote s back is exposed. Cumulative with Outnumbered.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Surrounding}{\insrsid6771226  - +1 bonus for completely surrounding your opponent. This is cumulative with outnumbered and flanked - since it\rquote 
s hard to surround someone without outnumbering and flanking them, this generally means a +3 bonus total.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 8.5.5 The Drop
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 If a character is not expecting an attack and has no reason to be on the defensive, the character\rquote s skill is 
considered to be Mediocre or equal to their Alertness, whichever is higher.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 8.5.6 Multiple Opponents
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 When fighting multiple opponents, a character still only makes one roll. All members of the attacking group who beat the character inflict damage as normal
. If the character beats all members of the attacking group, he may select one opponent (usually the one who rolled worst) and inflict damage on them.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 8.5.7 Defense
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 If a character is unarmed, or does not wish to attack, many physical skills (especially Tum
bling or Acrobatics) can be used in lieu of their combat rolls. If the defender wins the exchange, no matter how much they win by, it\rquote 
s treated as a scratch, though the GM may allow some defensive maneuvers, if in keeping with the skill - leaping out of the way of a sword blow is in keeping with leaping off a balcony.
\par If a character is using their combat skill and wishes to fight defensively, they may add +1 to their skill, but if they win the round, they inflict no damage. They may use this roll to perform
 maneuvers, such as getting away from their opponent, but may not perform maneuvers which affect their opponent.
\par Fighting defensively must be declared before dice are rolled. 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 8.6 Default Combat Modifiers
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Situation\tab \tab \tab Modifier
\par Superior Weapons*\tab \tab +1
\par Superior Armor\tab \tab +1
\par Superior Position\tab \tab +1
\par Superior Numbers\tab \tab +1
\par Flanking Opponent\tab \tab +1
\par Surrounding Opponent\tab +1
\par 
\par * See simple and advanced rules for alternate arms and armor rules. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs48\insrsid6771226 9. Magic and Supernormal Powers
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 There are few things less satisfying than a truly gen
eric magic system. Magic adds color, flavor and texture to any fantasy setting, and if those elements are generic, the impact on the setting is obvious. Because Fate is designed to be plugged into a setting and reflect its specifics, a generic system woul
d hardly be appropriate. Instead, we\rquote 
ve included a variety of sample systems to give a sense of some possible approaches. Any one of them is usable, but they are ultimately more useful as guidelines towards the sort of customization that will help bring out the specific feel of a setting.

\par In general, magic systems are based off the initial purchase of one or more magical aspects, which then open up special skills or extras that can be purchased. Purchasing more magical aspect levels may open up additional new skills and extras.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 9.1 Level Based Magic:  The Great Library
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 
In the world of Ald, magic is a structured, academic affair, and there is no greater center of magical learning than the Great Library. It is said that every spell ever written is somewhere in its miles and miles of bookshelves.
\par Characters looking to be mages must purchase a Magical Talent aspect. After that aspect is bought, the player may purchase a Cast Cantrips skill, as well as the aspect Magical Initiation. A character may potentially p
urchase up to 9 circles of Magical Initiation, and with each level a new Circle spellcasting skill (such as \'d2First Circle Spellcasting\'d3) is available.
\par Mages must prepare their spells at the beginning of the day by studying them from spellbooks. The number 
of spells in a given Circle which the mage can have prepared is equal to the number of skill ranks invested in the skill (equal to the skill value +1). Once cast, spells are no longer available until prepared again.
\par By default, spells do not require a skill roll to cast. However, the skill roll may be called for to target a spell, or to cast it under particularly trying circumstances.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 9.1.1 Ideas for adapting
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 This system assumes that there is a pre-existing spell list, broken into 10 levels from 0-9, and th
at a high degree of character advancement (enough to accumulate 10 aspects) is appropriate. If perchance no such system is available, it can easily be adapted to other level-based systems simply by changing the number of levels, usually reducing them. If 
a
n even larger list of spells is desired, simply increase the number of spell levels in a Circle. For instance, in a system with 20 spell levels, each Circle (and thus aspect level) might represent 5 spell levels; the skill level in that Circle would deter
mine how many spells in that Circle could be cast each day. 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 9.2 Combinative Magic: The Brass Compass
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 The world is balanced perfectly between the four points: Earth, Air, Fire and Water. Hedge witches may claim some power over one element or another, but tr
ue mages know that power comes from the balance of the four, and the danger that comes of imbalance.
\par There are 4 magical aspects and 4 magical skills in this system. The Aspects are Initiate of Fire, Initiate of Earth, Initiate of Air and Initiate of Water
, each representing a tie to the respective elemental force. To be a mage requires only one level of one of these aspects, but such a mage will have access to a far more limited }{\insrsid5639858 range of power than a more well-}{\insrsid6771226 
rounded practitioner of magic would.
\par The four magical skills (and their uses) are:
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Evocation}{\insrsid6771226 
 - Evocation is the preferred skill for combat, and is used for quick, usually forceful, expressions of power. For more sustained effects, summoning and mastery are usually more appropriate, but what it lacks i
n duration and finesse, it makes up in speed and power. Evocation is the favored skill of Fire Mages.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Summoning}{\insrsid6771226  - The skill for bringing amounts of an element into existence and roughly shaping it (mastery is more useful for that, and the two skills are hi
ghly complementary). It is also useful for summoning creatures of the elements, but mastery is required to bind them. Summoning is favored by Earth Mages.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Mastery}{\insrsid6771226  - Mastery is the ability to shape and control existing elements. It is arguably the most pote
nt of the skills of magic, but it is also entirely dependant on the presence of material with which to work. Mastery is favored by Air Mages, who are rarely without a source of their element.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Dispelling}{\insrsid6771226  - Beyond removing elemental matter, this is also the 
skill best suited to protection. While Mastery may allow a mage who takes his time to protect himself, only dispelling is fast enough to be usable in combat, and against evocations. Water mages favor this skill and its propensity to wear away any resistan
ce with time.
\par Spellcasting is started by determining what element and skill is involved. Usually this is obvious, but in some cases more than one element may apply. In those situations, the GM may either allow a partial effect (such as destroying just the w
ater in mud) or may rule that the mage must use their weakest aspect or skill. It is worth noting, living beings are considered to be a perfectly balanced combination of elements (Earth for form, Water for blood, Air for breath and Fire for life), so are 
very hard to target directly with any magics.
\par The next issue to determine is one of scope - how much of an element is summoned, shaped or dispelled, or how much force is deployed in an attack. The maximum scope is determined by the aspect level of the appro
priate element. Scope is best judged roughly by the amount of material worked with, which breaks down according to the table below.
\par After element and scope have been determined, the character rolls the appropriate skill against the difficulty listed in the table. If appropriate, that difficulty is also the number a target must roll against to resist an effect.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Elemental Magic}{\insrsid6771226 
\par Rank\tab Scope*\tab \tab Difficulty
\par -\tab Spark\tab \tab Average
\par 1\tab Finger\tab \tab Fair
\par 2\tab Fist\tab \tab Good
\par 3\tab Body\tab \tab Great
\par 4\tab Horse\tab \tab Superb
\par 5\tab House\tab \tab Epic
\par 6\tab Castle\tab \tab Legendary
\par 
\par * - Dispelling generally works as one level higher scope against summoned material. As such, 2 ranks of Fire magic could dispel a fist sized natural fire, or a body-sized magical one.\tab \tab 
\par The character may not generate an effect with a scope greater than their appropriate aspect level.
\par It is also possible for a mage to summon elementals. These are simple creatures defined by a single aspect - Elemental (of the appropriate type). The level o
f that aspect is equal to the rank required to summon one and sets its difficulty. Thus, a tiny fire elemental (Fire Elemental 1) is a difficulty of Fair.
\par To bind an elemental, the character must first summon it (roll summoning skill vs. difficulty) then bind it (mastery vs. difficulty).   A Mage may only have one elemental bound at a time. It\rquote 
s worth noting that elementals are fairly obvious and have no real means to hide themselves.   An elemental may be dispelled with a successful Dispel against their difficulty, using either their element or the opposed one (Fire v. Water, Earth v. Air).

\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 9.2.1 Ideas for adapting
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Long winded as it may be, the underlying principle is simple - a set of aspects and a set of skills, with aspects determining power and skills d
enoting, well, skill. What exactly the aspects and skills are is almost irrelevant. Elements were used in this example because they\rquote 
re a classic motif, but a solid magical system could be built off any logical (or mythical) combination. Imagine similar sys
tems where the aspects are the Seven Deadly Sins, the Muses, the seasons, the phases of the moon, a different set of elements or anything else that strikes one\rquote s fancy. 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 9.3 Improvisational Magic: The Door to Shadow
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 The gates have opened, and evil walks up
on the earth in ways it has not for centuries. Around the corner and just out of the corner of your eye, it lurks, growing in power. Our only hope are those unlikely few, the mad, the destined and the unlucky, who have seen this threat for what it is and 
are fighting to stop it.
\par This is a simple, narrative system for playing a somewhat fast and loose game where magic is important, but it is not necessarily central. Mage characters need to purchase a Magical Talent aspect and a spellcasting skill. It is poss
ible that those go under other names, such as Wicca or Thaumaturge with their Old Magick and Thaumaturgy skills. Generally speaking, this is just for color, but it may have some game effect (see below). The spellcasting skill (in whatever form it takes) c
an be bought without an appropriate aspect, but trying to use it to cast spells is exceptionally dangerous (see Feedback, below).
\par To cast a spell, simply determine its difficulty and make a spellcasting roll to meet or exceed the difficulty level, then mark off a level of the aspect. As such, yes, the aspect limits the number of spells that can be cast per day, and as such, it
\rquote s dangerous to burn it for a reroll - as such, having another aspect to represent magical education, like Occult Studies or Ancient Lore can be quite useful, and what often allows a more experienced mage defeat a more powerful one.
\par Difficulty defaults to Average (0), and is increased or decreased by the effects of the spell as follows.
\par The spell\rquote s scope encompasses...
\par \tab Nothing: +0
\par \tab The Caster: +1
\par \tab A room: +2
\par \tab A building: +3
\par \tab A town: +4
\par \tab A state: +5
\par If the spell targets...
\par \tab No One: +0 }{\insrsid5639858 Difficulty}{\insrsid6771226 
\par }{\insrsid5639858 \tab 1 Person: +1 D}{\insrsid6771226 ifficulty
\par \tab Small Group: +2 Difficulty
\par \tab Neighborhood: +3 Difficulty
\par \tab Town: +4 Difficulty
\par Note: Most spells either have a number of targets or a scope, not both. Thus, a spell to put everyone in a room to sleep would be based on targets, while one to illuminate the room would use scope. When in doubt, use the higher difficulty.
\par If the spell is...
\par \tab Irritating or inconvenient: +1 Difficulty
\par \tab Damaging: +2 Difficulty
\par \tab Incapacitating: +3 Difficulty
\par \tab Fully transformative: +4 Difficulty
\par \tab Mind Altering: +2 Difficulty (over and above other modifiers - mind control is effectively incapacitating and affects the mind)
\par \tab Instantly Lethal: Impossible
\par If the Casting takes...
\par \tab A few moments (i.e. in combat): +1 Difficulty
\par \tab A few minutes: +0 Difficulty
\par \tab A few Hours: -1 Difficulty
\par \tab A few Days: -2 Difficulty
\par If the spell requires:
\par \tab Nothing: +1 Difficulty
\par \tab Easily acquirable, portable components: +0 Difficulty
\par \tab Components are very inconvenient or hard to acquire: -1 Difficulty
\par \tab Components are very inconvenient and hard to acquire: -2 Difficulty
\par Note: if the spell requires components, their exact nature is determined by the GM - it\rquote s cheating to decide that you
r spell needs a rare ingredient you just happen to have on hand. This drawback is generally only appropriate for researched spells (see below)
\par If the spell lasts...
\par \tab An instant (generally long enough for a combat attack): +0 Difficulty
\par \tab A few seconds: +1 Difficulty
\par \tab A few minutes: +2 Difficulty
\par \tab A few Hours: +3 Difficulty
\par \tab A few days: +4 Difficulty
\par \tab A few Months: +5 Difficulty
\par \tab A few Years: +6 Difficulty
\par \tab Forever: +7 Difficulty
\par Also, optionally for those with a more dramatic bent:
\par The spell affects the story by...
\par \tab Advancing the plot: -1 Difficulty
\par \tab Doing something someone could do with a mundane skill: +1 Difficulty
\par \tab Doing something that someone else in the party could do mundanely: +1 Difficulty (in addition to mundane penalty)
\par \tab Jumping over a large amount of plot: +2 Difficulty or more
\par \tab Bypassing an entire story: +4 Difficulty or more
\par And lastly, one unique modifier:
\par \tab Inconvenient Timing: -1 Difficulty or more. Inconvenient timing is mostly just useful for villains, as it represents spells that can only occur under certain circumstances \tab (\'d2when the stars are right\'d3
). This generally gives a plot reason why a villain can be casting a world-destroying spell, but still be at a level that the PCs can manage.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 9.3.1 Research
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 It is also p
ossible to spend some time researching a spell in advance, either preparing it (which requires a magical toolkit of sorts, depending on the type of magic - a big cauldron for example) or researching it (which requires an occult library). In either case, a
 research roll is made against the difficulty of the spell, and if successful, subtract 1 from the difficulty of the spell. The GM may award additional bonuses for extreme degrees of success.
\par Researched spells are generally not re-usable. Duplicating an already researched spell requires another research roll.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 9.3.2 Feedback
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Magic is dangerous stuff. The number of aspects the character has represents the amount they can safely handle, but sometimes a caster needs to push }{\insrsid5639858 himself}{
\insrsid6771226  a little farther. If all of the caster\rquote 
s Magical Talent aspects are checked off, and he still wishes to cast a spell, determine difficulty and roll skill as normal. If the spell is successful with at least a MOS of 1, all is well. However, if the spell fails, or succeeds exactly, th
e powers the character is working with get out of their control. This is treated as an attack on the character with a severity equal to the difficulty of the spell plus the degree by which the character failed (0, if the }{\insrsid5639858 spell succeeds}{
\insrsid6771226 ). The character rolls to defend against this attack with their aspect level. Characters without a Magic Talent aspect default to Mediocre on this roll.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 9.3.3 Ideas for adapting
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 As written, this system is functional but bland. Fortunately, it takes only a little tweaking to give it some flavor. It\rquote 
s possible to give the various magical schools some mechanical impact. Generally, it\rquote s best to makes this a +1 to skill in certain circumstances and -1 in other circumstances. Try to make the circumstances roughly equal. For example, t
he Alchemists of Bin-Assam practice a magical tradition rich in potions, smokes and exotic ingredients. The receive a +1 bonus to skill when casting a spell with required components. However, they are given to ornate, overly complicated rituals, and take 
a -1 penalty to skill when trying to cast spells more quickly than over the course over a few hours.
\par Modifiers that reflect the \'d2rules of magic\'d3 also add a lot to the flavor of a setting. Perhaps spells receive a bonus when you know the target\rquote s true name, 
or have a symbolic link to the target, such as a voodoo doll. Perhaps spells are more powerful at dawn or dusk. Some rules don\rquote t even need rules: something like \'d2curses return threefold\'d3 is better played out than left to a mechanic.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 9.4 Stunt Based Magic: The Great Lighthouse
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 
In the city of Ald, the Great Lighthouse has held off attackers of every stripe for generations. At its peak rests and unquenchable flame, which adepts can direct to strike anything out to the horizon. Great as that power is, it only t
ouches the surface of the potential of this mystical flame. Initiates who immerse themselves in it and survive become adepts, carrying a small amount of fire within them, and may use it to fuel their sorceries.
\par This fire magic is represented by two things: a spellcasting skill, called \'d2Pyromancy\'d3, and a number of \'d2stunts\'d3
. By using the skill, the mage may start fires without kindling or tools, and even produce small fires (Fair=matchlight, Superb=a large torch) from their body without fuel, though this requ
ires too much concentration to be useful in combat (without a stunt). They may control fires (Fair=Torch, Superb = Bonfire) in showy ways, changing colors and sculpting shapes. They may passively use their skill as a defense against fire and heat. More po
werful effects require using a stunt.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 9.4.1 Stunts
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Characters spend skill points for \'d2Stunts\'d3
. Performing a stunt allows the character to do something more dramatic with the skill. Each stunt bought gives the character a circle next to the skill, which refr
eshes in the same manner as aspects, and which can be checked off to perform a stunt. Thus, an experienced Fire Mage, with 3 stunts might express it as:
\par \tab Pyromancy: Good (OOO)
\par This would cost 6 skill ranks total: 3 to bring the skill to Good, and one for each stunt.
\par The first skill rank must be purchased in conjunction with the \'d2Pyromancer\'d3 aspect.
\par To use a stunt, simply describe the desired action and check off a circle. Here are some guidelines that may help give a sense of what stunts can do:
\par A stunt should never last any longer than a scene.
\par A stunt generally translates into a single effect: A bolt of fire, a wall of flame, lighting something on fire. More sophisticated effects require multiple stunts.
\par A stunt can allow magic to be used as a combat skill. This is limited by the effect: A bolt of fire might work for only a single attack, but a protective wall could last a scene.
\par Spells which affect multiple targets take a -1 penalty to the roll for each target beyond the first.
\par Spells which simulate weapon
s are fine, but they are bound by the general limitations of the weapons - i.e. creating a perpetual flame bolt that is held in the hand and using it as a sword is fine, but creating a 50 foot bolt claiming its a sword isn't really feasible.
\par The addition of magic to a fight can grant a situational advantage (i.e. a +1 bonus).
\par Stunts are refreshed after a full nights rest or meditation in the presence of a (torch sized or larger) fire. A desperate Fire Mage may also immerse his hands (or other parts) and suffer bad burns (automatically suffering an \'d2injured\'d3
 result) to refresh his stunts. 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\insrsid6771226 Sample Pyromancy Stunts
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\insrsid6771226 Bolt of Flame}{\insrsid6771226 
\par An old favorite, this blast of flame shoots from the caster's hand or eyes with the intent of incinerating the target. Used at range, this attack grants no bonus for superior armor, and if the target is wearing flammable clothes of metal armor, that quali
fies as inferior armor for calculating bonuses. Range is usually line of sight, and the exact appearance of the bolt is shaped by the fancy of the caster. 
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Wall of Flame}{\insrsid6771226 
\par Another classic, a wall of flame bursts into existence, either around the caster, or so
mewhere nearby. Passing through the wall subjects the target to an attack from the caster's skill as if they had been hit by a bolt of flame. It's possible to surround a target in a wall of fire with an attack that generates a hurt result, and it's possib
le to directly target something with the wall (light it under their feet) with a injured result. 
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Brave The Inferno}{\insrsid6771226 
\par Ignore damage from any single fire for as long as it lasts and as long as the character is exposed to it. This allows ignoring a single attack, walking around in a burning house, or passing through a wall of fire unharmed.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\insrsid6771226 Other Stunts
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 \tab Shape a ladder out of a bonfire and climb it to a nearby window
\par \tab Increase the intensity of a forge to the point where it can melt magical metal
\par \tab Set something very large on fire
\par \tab Make a fire very hard to extinguish
\par \tab Study a fire and find out what it's burning
\par \tab Read a book by burning it
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\insrsid6771226 What Fire Magic Cannot Do
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 \tab Boil someone's insides
\par \tab Burn something non-flammable (though it can surround it in flame)
\par \tab Summon fire creatures or otherwise give life to fire
\par \tab Scry or teleport through fires
\par \tab Find information from cold ashes
\par \tab Geas
\par Pyromancy does have certain limitations. A Fire Magi who is submerged in water (or other liquid) cannot perform any fire magic until the next 
full moon. Significant partial submersion (even a bad enough rainstorm) is enough, so Fire Magi are very careful around water which has created a legend that it is somewhat more baneful to them than it genuinely is. This has also inspired some peculiar ba
t
hing habits. In the south, sand and oil are more common than water anyway, so there is no problem, but in the midlands it's definitely an issue. Interestingly, snow and ice are not considered water (unless they melt), a loophole that the small number of n
orthern Fire Magi take advantage of, though the idea of a \'d2snow bath\'d3 is disconcerting to those of a less hardy nature.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 9.4.2 Ideas for Adapting
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Stunts are really designed to serve as a middle ground between handwaving magical effects and rigid bookkeeping 
of capabilities. Coming up with additional magic systems is as easy as deciding on the incidental effects, deciding what the stunts are capable of, and determining if there\rquote s a geas or other limitations.
\par The exact definition of what a stunt is depends stro
ngly on the campaign. While it is possible that it may represent a concrete limit, that is not necessary. Like aspects, they are more of a narrative limitation, and because of that, GMs looking to blur the line of how often magic can be used are encourage
d to allow appropriate aspect boxes to be used in lieu of stunt boxes. Of course, in games where wizards are expected to have a fixed number of spells per day (or some other cycle), no further explanation is really necessary.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 9.5 Interpretive Magic: Sorcery on a Budget
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Sometimes magic just isn\rquote 
t easy. Whether because of the overwhelming disbelief of the vast swell of humanity, or some natural protection that keeps the world from accepting the supernatural. Whatever the case, necessity has made magic both subtle and rare.
\par The single most important component of any spell is how blatant it is. Blatancy is mostly a measure of how flashy or obvious the working of power is - it\rquote s a measure of how wrong whatever is being done appears to any bystanders. This puts ver
y practical limits on anything done with magic - more often than not, if a task can be done mundanely, it\rquote s much easier to do so. This is why most wizards carry guns.
\par When using magic, players are encouraged to describe effects in terms of how they would appear in the movie version of their story. Now, this method depends on the player wanting to describe things interestingly - if players are more interested in describ
ing things as flatly as possible in an attempt to drive down difficulties, the GM should do two things - raise the difficulties to an appropriate level, and consider using a different magic system.
\par Magic using characters should have some sort of aspect to describe their type of magic. This can be as general as \'d2Wizard\'d3 or as specific as \'d2Mystical Master of Cheese\'d3
. These give a general guideline as to the types of magic the character can perform, and the GM is perfectly entitled to grant bonuses when she fee
ls a magical effect is particularly in keeping with the aspect, or nix one that seems to have nothing to do with it (unless, of course, there\rquote s a really good explanation). The level of this aspect represents the character\rquote s \'d2
special effects budget\'d3 for magic (to wit, the most powerful spell effect they can manage). The character also has a spellcasting skill, which they roll when casting and attempt to meet or exceed the difficulty level for the \'d2budget.\'d3
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Magical Budget
\par }{\insrsid6771226 Asp.\tab Difficulty\tab Description
\par 1\tab Fair\tab \tab A set of bongos and interpretive dance
\par 2\tab Good\tab \tab Public access - a couple of guys with a camcorder
\par 3\tab Great\tab \tab Cable television production
\par 4\tab Superb\tab Television \'d2Mini-Series Event\'d3
\par 5\tab Epic\tab \tab Blockbuster Movie
\par 6\tab Legendary\tab F/X extravaganza
\par 
\par Some budgetary notes:
\par The more area or targets a spell affects, the more camera angles required, and in turn, the more budget.
\par Remember, the target is part of the audience. As such, spells that quietly and invisibly choke someone or stop their heart won\rquote t work, because they won\rquote t no
tice them. You need to invest some in making them feel it. As such, the very least directly damaging spells require a minimum of a cable TV budget. Indirect damage (like burning someone by catching their house on fire) is a different beast entirely.

\par A character can temporarily boost their budget by checking off aspects. Each aspect checked off in this fashion raises the maximum budget for the next magical effect by one. 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 9.5.1 Ideas for adapting
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Right off the bat, GMs may require that magical aspects be a l
ittle more specific, with the idea that a real wizard will have aspects in things like Evocation, Thaumaturgy or Summonings. However you think magic should work, toss it in there.
\par This is an odd system in that it is probably entirely unappealing to a large segment of gamers. It depends on a lot of trust between the players and GM and requires a lot of interpretation on the GM\rquote s part. If it doesn\rquote t work for you, don
\rquote t worry about it. However, if this seems like your cup of tea, the possibilities for interpretation are probably already suggesting themselves.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 9.6 Minor Powers: Skin Dance
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\i\insrsid6771226 
When the Weasel first talked to me I was so drunk that I just took it all at face value. Apparently, I agreed to some serious mojo-binding stuff, and in return I would get the Weasel\rquote 
s power. I guess I must have agreed, because I woke up that morning up inside my left pants leg.}{\insrsid6771226 
\par In preparation for a threat only hinted at, the lords of the beasts have approached worthy humans and offered them the gift of skinchanging - the abilit
y to turn into their patron creature. Despite the questionable value of some of these blessings, these skinchangers are prepared to use the little power at their disposal to defend mankind...as soon as they figure out what they\rquote 
re defending it against.
\par Skinchangers buy an aspect in the appropriate animal, and gain the ability to transform into that animal. It\rquote 
s difficult for a human to adapt to the workings of the animal physiology, so it is necessary for them to buy ranks in a skill called (animal) mobility (weasel mobility or what have you). This is a difficult skill to master, so it defaults to Poor (see 
\'d2Difficult Skills\'d3). This skill is the general baseline for activity in the creature\rquote s form. If the creature can fly, things are doubly difficult, and default to terrible.
\par Many creatures have special abilities. Some are intrinsic- a weasel is small and a fish breathes underwater, and there\rquote s no need to reflect those with skills or aspects. Others have abilities better reflected with aspects - a bloodhound\rquote 
s keen senses or a ferret\rquote s speed. These aren\rquote t mandatory, but if the player wishes to take advantage of the animal\rquote 
s abilities, buying the appropriate aspects is a good idea. Some abilities are very specific to the creature, such as a skunk\rquote s spray. In th
ose cases, the character should buy a skill to reflect that ability. That skill defaults to the same level as the mobility skill did, and can never be higher than the mobility skill.
\par Some animals are also better suited to combat than others. Any skinchange
r can use their mobility skill to dodge, but those gifted with natural weapons should buy a combat skill to use them. This skill has the same starting default as mobility, and can never be bought higher than the current mobility score.
\par Lastly, any form cap
able of fine manipulation should buy a manipulation skill to represent it. As with other skills, it defaults to the same level mobility does and cannot be bought any higher than the current mobility skill level. This skill is appropriate for simians, but 
may also be appropriate for some small mammals and birds.
\par Characters should not have more than one animal form. If they do, the skills for one form do not translate to the other form, unless the forms are very similar, like a squirrel and a chipmunk.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 9.6.1 Ideas for adapting
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 
The underlying model here is simple - an aspect that introduces a minor power can work just fine if it also requires at least one skill to use the ability. If the aspect is particularly useful, then it should require more skills. With th
at idea in mind, it\rquote s easy to model any sort of knack or gimmick, from ESP to Breath Control. This is also the idea behind a number of magic systems. This is a good model to simulate a genre with limited powers, like some urban fantasy or pulp.

\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs48\insrsid6771226 10. Utilities
\par }{\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 10.1 Sample Aspects
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\insrsid6771226 Anger
\par }{\insrsid6771226 The character\rquote s rage simmers just below the surface, awaiting opportunity to burst.
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Vent his frustration, usually through explosive action towards whatever he\rquote s mad at.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Cause the character to lose his temper at an inappropriate moment. Interfere with any action that requires calm.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Bookworm
\par }{\insrsid6771226 The character is an academic, well versed in all manner of obscure lore. His knowledge, unfortunately, is almost entirely from books, and theory is not always the same as practice.
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Dig up an obscure fact or other bit of knowledge at the right. Research like a fiend.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Cause problems when the character is faced with the need to apply his knowledge under the stress of \'d2Real World\'d3 conditions.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Cowardly
\par }{\insrsid6771226 The character is a firm believer in the better part of valor, either out of meekness, deep self interest, or some other motivator. 
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Run, hide, or otherwise get away from something dangerous.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Inspire the character to flee when he really }{\insrsid5639858 needs}{\insrsid6771226  to stand his ground.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Curse of Toads
\par }{\insrsid6771226 When the character tells a lie, a live toad pops out of his mouth.
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Gross someone out, or convince someone who knows of the curse that he is honest.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Complicate things when lies would be more convenient.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Duty
\par }{\insrsid6771226 The character owes a duty to some one or thing which should come out of creation. Alternately, the character may simply take all of his responsibilities very seriously.
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Perform an action which directly upholds the duty.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Present a player a choice between upholding his duty or doing something more practical. Raise an issue of responsibility at an inconvenient moment.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Intelligent
\par }{\insrsid6771226 The character is smart, simple as that.
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Know useful things, or find them out if they aren\rquote t known.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Unless there are monsters that specifically like eating big brains, there\rquote s not much the GM can do with this.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Meticulous
\par }{\insrsid6771226 The character is very thorough in his approach to almost everything.
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Get a bonus to any task where he has the time and resources to do a thorough job, \'d2discover\'d3 that he packed just the right tool.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Interfere with the character being spontaneous.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Onianos
\par }{\insrsid6771226 A curved blade carved from the purest Moonstone, this sword has been passed down through generations of heroes. In the hands of the unworthy, its edge is dull and its balance shoddy, but in t
he hands of a true (or potential) hero, it strikes sharp and true.
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Swordfight, or have the sword conveniently available.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Steal the sword. Require some ritual to renew the sword\rquote s magic.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Panasta Dados
\par }{\insrsid6771226 Panasta Dados is the Master of Thieves of the city of Alverado, and at some point he took the character under his wing and taught him some of what he knows.
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Perform a thiefly task, \'d2Here\rquote s a trick Old Pan taught me.\'d3 Get some information about Alverado, get information directly from Panasta.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Have Pan call in a favor. Have Pan\rquote s enemies try to strike at him through the character.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Priest
\par }{\insrsid6771226 The character is a member of the priesthood, and is expected to support the appropriate dogma, as well as accept whatever duties, responsibilities and powers come with the position.
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Give a stirring sermon. Resist the powers antithetical to his faith. Attempt to use the resources of his church. 
\par The GM might invoke this to: Deliver inconvenient orders from a superior. Present temptations that contradict the Priest\rquote s Dogma. Raise the ire of opposed religions.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Self Destructive
\par }{\insrsid6771226 For whatever reason, the character seeks
 his own destruction, though he is unwilling to take direct action to do something about it. Instead, he throws himself wholeheartedly into dangerous situations in the hopes that this time will be his last.
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Do something stupid and dangerous.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Keep a character from doing the safe, reasonable thing.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Raello
\par }{\insrsid6771226 The character\rquote s family estate, it is a place of rest and refuge from the troubles of the world.
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Draw upon the resources of the house.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Threaten the house.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Treacherous
\par }{\insrsid6771226 The character has a knack for betrayal. He\rquote s the one who shows up on the movie screen and everyone watching knows that he\rquote s the one who\rquote s going to whisper lies in the king\rquote 
s ear and try to seduce the naive princess. Betrayal comes easily to the character, and while he may be steadfast and true in the end, it would be so easy not to be.
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Lie, spy or generally connive.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Incite suspicious reactions from NPCs, especially when the character is telling the truth. Offer opportunities to stab comrades in the back.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Veteran
\par }{\insrsid6771226 The character is the survivor of many battles, and the experience has shaped him. This is appropriate for a seasoned campaigner who has seen many battles (in contrast to Veteran of Gishal Falls, below).
\par A player might invoke this aspect to: Keep his wits about him in a fight. Assess a tactical situation. Pitch camp in unfriendly country.
\par The GM might invoke this to: Invoke flashbacks. Introduce old rivals from the other side of the battlefield.
\par }{\b\insrsid6771226 Veteran of Gishal Falls
\par }{\insrsid6771226 The Battle of Gishal Falls was fought over the course of 4 months in the swampy, disease-infested valley below the falls. Both the Nadulians and the Asts consider the battle a defeat, and the casualty rates on both sides were obscene.

\par A player might invoke this aspect to: As Veteran, but also to resist disease or carry on activities in a swamp.
\par The GM might invoke this to: As Veteran, but the GM now knows who the opposing side was, and what people think of the battle. Some may consider the character a reminder of the Army\rquote 
s embarrassment, or resent them for surviving while a loved one did not.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 10.2 More Aspects
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Amnesia -The character has a hole in his memory of some size. The good and ill of this are somewhat subject to GM whim.
\par Banjo -The Demon Horse. He\rquote s fast, tough and smart, but he also eats meat. Especially rabbits.
\par Barbarian -Raised in the wilds, this character may be good at hunting and fighting, but lacking in social graces.
\par Courtier -Experienced with the ebb and flow of courtly intrigue, this is useful for dealing with those intrigues, but less useful for convincing an angry mob that you\rquote re really one of them.
\par Delusional - The character has some firmly held delusion. This tends to be useful on those occasions the delusion is useful (think Don Quixote), but otherwise problematic.
\par Fae-touched - The character knows something of the ways of Faerie, but this comes with some drawbacks, such as an aversion to Iron, the necessity of an invitation to enter a home, or just the attention of faeries.
\par Famous - The character is well known, which is useful for dealing with people who like him, but less useful when trying to avoid attention.
\par Holy - The character\rquote s convictions run so deep as to be a beacon in the darkness. This beacon may provide illumination, but it also is likely to draw attention.
\par Fop - A cultured gentleman can turn to excess. While Fops are usually skilled in social arts, they are also prone to a variety of vices, and have a most unwholesome reputation.
\par Gambler- Know when to hold \lquote em, know when to fold \lquote em, but very rarely know when not to play the game.
\par Hunted - Someone (or something) is after the character. Useful for evading or confronting pursuers, but with obvious drawbacks
\par Irish - Useful for drinking, brawling and spinning yarns, less good for stopping drinking and keeping your temper.
\par Kind - Kindness is a virtue treasured by healers and those who bring succor, but it is ill-suited to many of life\rquote s cruelties.
\par Large - Useful when being big and strong comes in handy, but less useful when trying to do things like hide (or buy clothes that fit).
\par Ninja - Can you ever really have enough ninjas?
\par Rich -Outside of the events of play, the ch}{\insrsid5639858 aracter has significant wealth, }{\insrsid6771226 which is useful in many ways. Sadly, what he has, so many others want...
\par Rival - The character has a rival who he wants to defeat in some fashion. While this aspect may help with the rivalry, the rival himself is likely to cause problems.
\par Strong - Break things!
\par Vengeful - The character\rquote s been wronged, and seeks to make it right. This is useful for pursuing that revenge, but such focus can often turn into tunnel vision.
\par Weapon Master - The character kicks ass with weapons. People who kick ass this much tend to draw attention from others out to prove how much they kick ass.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 10.3 Skill Lists
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 There is no one skill list that can apply to all games. The nature of the game should shape the skill list to reflect what }{\insrsid5639858 sorts of activities are}{
\insrsid6771226  important in the game. Skills are measures of how characters distinguish themselves. The idea of \'d2party balance\'d3
 hinges on the idea that each member of the group contributes something unique to the whole. The idea was originally couched in purely tactical terms, but }{\insrsid5639858 it\rquote s}{\insrsid6771226 
 more broadly applicable.   If each character in a given group has a particular area in which th
ey excel, everyone is given an opportunity to take the spotlight from time to time. Naturally, there is also the question of genre - a computer programming skill will be out of place in a game of sword and sorcery.
\par When creating a skill list, it's importan
t to keep two key elements in mind: there must be enough skills to allow each character an arena to excel in, and skills must be more finely defined in areas that will be important to the game. In the absence of a defined skill list, it's often useful to 
look at skills in terms of a few broad categories, and whether you want the skills in those categories defined in a broad, general or specific fashion.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 10.3.1 Skill Categories
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 The most general categories of skills are Academic, Artistic, Athletic, Combat, Criminal, Magical, Perception, Professional, Social, Survival, which break down as follows.

