\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 11.1.3 Modifiers
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 It's easy to add bonuses and penalties to d6 rolls, and there are numerous ways to do it. For Fate, bonuses and penalties are applied as \'d2Bonus Dice\'d3 and \'d2Penalty Dice
\'d3; for instance, a \'d2+1\'d3 modifier becomes one bonus die, while a \'d2-1\'d3 modifier becomes one
 penalty die. Bonus dice are added to the total number of dice rolled, but do not change the number of dice counted. This means that if a player is rolling 3 dice, and gets two bonus dice, they would roll 5 dice, but only count the best 3. Penalty dice wo
rk the same way, except the player must count the worst dice. Bonus dice and penalty dice cancel out, so a player should never be rolling both at once.
\par Modifiers can be applied for a number of reasons. Low quality tools or a lack of tools might add a penalt
y die (or dice) while having high quality tools may grant a bonus. Similarly, doing a task quickly might cause a penalty, while taking the time to be careful might grant a bonus.   Distractions might be penalties, while extra resources on hand may provide
 bonuses. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 11.1.4 Aspects
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Aspects are maybe used in Fated6 to do one of 2 things:
\par  Turn a single d6 into a 5
\par or
\par  Reroll all dice
\par It\rquote s important to note that all dice are considered to be on the table for purposes of bonuses and penalties. Thus, if a charac
ter with an Average skill rolls with a penalty die rolls 2,2,4, he can check off an aspect to turn the 2 into a 5 to make the result 2,4,5, but he will still need to chose the two worst dice (the 3 and 4). Mind you, in this case, invoking the aspect has c
hanged a result of 4 into a 6, enough to make a difference in many circumstances.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 11.1.5 Fate Points
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 In addition to the dramatic uses of fate points, the mechanical benefit is to add 1 more die to a roll. While auctions are an option, no more than 1 fate di
e can apply to any single roll.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs48\insrsid6771226 12.  Constructing Organizations with Fate
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 
Organizations are built in much the same way that character's are, with both aspects and skills, albeit from somewhat different lists. While it is possible to build organizations in 
a phased manner, unless multiple organizations are being created at the same time (such as for a conspiracy game, see below) there is little real reason to do so. GMs are encouraged to make use of the pyramid }{\insrsid5639858 cheat sheet}{
\insrsid6771226 . 
\par Organizations should be built on the model of 1 aspect per 4 skills, though \'d2freebie\'d3 aspects may be appropriate.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 12.1 Organization Aspects
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 As with characters, aspects reflect the nature of the organization. It should be possible for someone to read the list of aspects and get a sense of t
he nature of the organization. As such, organization's aspects should usually encompass the scope and nature of the organization.
\par The scope of the organization can encompass a number of elements, like the size of the membership or how far-reaching the orga
nization may be. Scope is not synonymous with influence, that's covered by skills, but it is complementary. Scope is rarely measured precisely, but as a rule of thumb it correlates with how many areas of influence (see the influence skill, below) the orga
nization extends to on a roughly 1/1 basis. Scope also sets the default difficulty for many internal activities, especially of an administrative nature. If cope is not clearly implicit in the aspect, assume it to be equal to the highest ranking aspect.

\par Other aspects should give insight into the nature of the organization, and are things like Sub-Genius, Criminal or Mercantile. These aspects should give a sense of the sort of activities the organization pursues, or what manner of philosophy it follows.

\par These are not the only aspects an organization may have, but they are the most common. Other aspect may reinforce skills (\'d2Conspiracy\'d3 or \'d2Rich\'d3) or may be something else entirely.
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 12.3 Organization Skills
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 
Skills measure those things the organization can do, such as exercising influence or drawing upon resources. While there are only a few skill types that an organization may take, they are much like knowledge skills in that they may be taken multiple times
 to specify the area of use (So an organization might have Influence: England and Influence: France). 
\par Organization skills have very specific uses, and as such cannot be freely substituted for each other. As such, if an organization has a great deal of infl
uence, and wants to use that influence to secure resources, that should be represented by a resources skill (or can default to mediocre).
\par In general, organizations are bound to the same rules regarding the skill pyramid that characters are, though the GM may grant exceptions for special cases. 
\par The usual skills for organizations are as follows:
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Control (Region)}{\insrsid6771226  - This represents how much overt control the organization holds over a given area, usually in the form of institutionalized rule.
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Sway (Region)}{\insrsid6771226  - Sw
ay represents non-institutional power over a given area, be it due to respect, fear or any other appropriate motivator. Like control, sway is obvious, and it does much which control does. However, it is less effective than true control, and as such it is 
at a -1 to all actions.
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Influence (Region)}{\insrsid6771226 
 - This represents how much secret sway the organization has. Practically speaking, this works in the same way sway does (albeit at -2 from control), but unlike sway (which is obvious) there is no obvious tie back to the organization.
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Information (Region)}{\insrsid6771226  - This skill represents knowledge of current events in appropriate areas, and is most appropriate for organizations with decent intelligence and espionage arms. 
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Arms (type) }{\insrsid6771226 - Many organizations have access to a num
ber of rough and ready individuals willing to do (or prevent) harm on command. Because these rules are for organizations (rather than nations), the main differentiation is one of quality. A given arms score represents one military aspect of an organizatio
n, so if an organization has more than one military arm, more than one skill is appropriate.
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Resources (type)}{\insrsid6771226  - The type is usually money, but sometimes an organization has a great deal of some other sort of resource, like a trade commodity or a particular type of service.
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Unity}{\insrsid6771226  - This measures how unified the organization is with higher unity meaning less internal strife. High Unity organizations tend to be more stable.
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Administration}{\insrsid6771226  - The larger an organization is, the more of its resources it needs to commit to keeping itself in order, and this skill measures how effectively that's done.
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Communication}{\insrsid6771226  - The other side of the coin is communication, which is a measure of how effectively a message may be communicated within the organization. For a small orga
nization, this skill may be entirely irrelevant, but for a large organization, it can be critical. This skill is also highly complementary to high information skills.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\i\f184\fs26\insrsid6771226 12.2.1 Special Skills
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Many organizations will have at least one special skill which repre
sents something peculiar which that organization does which others may not. These special skills could be almost anything, depending on the nature of the setting and the organization, but some of the more common types include:
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Magic}{\insrsid6771226  - The organization has 
access to some manner of arcane arts, be it the blessings of the priests or ties to ancient secrets. This generally means the organization has access to spellcasters of some stripe or another, and the skill represents their quality and type. Much like arm
s, if the organization has access to multiple types, multiple skills are appropriate.
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Assassination}{\insrsid6771226  - The ability to quietly make people dead. Naturally, this is illegal pretty much everywhere, and had best be accompanied a great deal of secrecy.
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Secrecy}{\insrsid6771226  - 
This is a measure of how hard it is to find things out about the organization and (at higher levels) whether or not the organization exists at all. Whether this secrecy is an intentional conspiracy or merely the result of extreme obscurity can be determin
ed at creation.
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Reputation}{\insrsid6771226 
 - The opposite of secrecy, this is the public face of an organization insofar as it may deviate from the reality. Most organizations have an implicit reputation based upon their aspects and activities, but it is possible to put on a \'d2false face\'d3
, represented by this skill.
\par }{\cs24\b\i\insrsid6771226 Lore}{\insrsid6771226  - The organization has access to a large body of knowledge of some sort (as with arms: multiple lores mean multiple skills), and it\rquote 
s generally implicit that this is knowledge that may be hard to come by under other circumstances.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 12.3 Holdings
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 
It is also possible for an organization to spend skill points on holdings, such as safe houses or strongholds. The rules for these are similar to the rules for items, with each skill ranks translating into some sort of
 quality for the holding. Possible qualities include:
\par Fortified - The holding is protected in some way.
\par Hidden - The holding is difficult to find.
\par Isolated - The holding is far from civilization.
\par Ornate - The holding is impressive to behold
\par Big - The holding is extensive
\par Magical - The holding is magical in some way. This may be useful (it\rquote s a node of power) or decorative (it floats over a volcano\rquote s caldera). In general, if the magic provides some additional benefit (like defensibility), other qualities shou
ld be purchased
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li720\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin720\itap0 \f183\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cf1\insrsid6771226 Example: Creating an Organization
\par The Church of Saint Agnes (CSA) is a small militant order within the Quintarian church, dedicated to a warrior-priestess who martyred herself to protect a cloister of monks. CSA followers generally make themselves available to Quintarian priests }{
\cf1\insrsid5639858 traveling}{\cf1\insrsid6771226  to dangerous destinations.
\par The CSA is a very minor sect, so they\rquote re being built with only 3 aspects. Because they\rquote re a sect of a larger church with no real influence of their own, scope aspects don\rquote t seem appropriate. Instead, 2 aspects of \'d2Quintarian\'d3
 represent their tie to the mother church, while a single aspect of \'d2Militant\'d3 reflects their flavor.
\par A quick look at the aspect }{\cf1\insrsid5639858 cheat sheet}{\cf1\insrsid6771226  says that\rquote 
s 5 Averages, 2 Fairs and a Good. Because the pyramid only technically needs 3 Averages, that means 2 ranks could be put into holdings without breaking the pyramid. With that in mind:
\par The Good obviously goes into Arms to represent the Templars of the church. 
\par They\rquote re fairly well organized and well funded (it\rquote s a popular charity for soldiers) so Administration and Resources (Money) are Fair. 
\par At Average are Sway: Beve, Communication, and the special Skill \'d2Charity\'d3, which represents the good works (and subsequent good will received) the church pursues. 
\par The two remaining ranks are spent on chapterhouses in the Cities of Beve and Anas, with Beve being their main house (Thus the Sway). 
\par The final write up looks like:
