\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f183\fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 12.4 Using Organizations
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 Once play has begun, there are several benefits to having stats for organizations. It provides a good baseline for what various organizations may know and what their interests 
are. It also provides an excellent shorthand for dealing with NPCs from that organization. If the Knights of Anton have Arms (Knights) at Good, then Joe Nameless Knight can probably be considered to have a \'d2Good\'d3 in appropriate military skills.

\par Additionally, it provides a nicely abstracted way for organizations to come into conflict with one another and to resolve it with a minimum of headache. How likely are Walsingham\rquote s spies (Information (France): Good) to find out about John Ballard
\rquote s Jesuit Conspiracy (Secrecy: Fair) to assassinate the queen? Easily determined!
\par For games which use an \'d2off season\'d3, organization statistics can also be used to represent and resolve longer term conflicts.  Organizations may even have their own wound track for GMs wishing to }{\insrsid5639858 concentrate}{\insrsid6771226 
 on this element.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 12.5 The Conspiracy Game
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6771226 
One interesting option for using this system is as a preamble to another game. Allow each player to construct an organization in a phased fashion, and allow the interactions of the organizations and the choices of the players establish some of the backdro
p of the setting. The play of this is simple enough, but a few complications can spice it up:
\par Disallow player from making subsequent characters with membership in the organization they created.
\par At the end of each phase, have each player secretly write the name of the organizations closest ally or greatest enemy among the group. The GM looks at these secretly, and whenever there is a }{\insrsid5639858 match up}{\insrsid6771226 
 (including enemy to ally!) add an aspect to each organization called \'d2Connection to <name>\'d3. This means the two groups 
compliment each other well, but are also vulnerable to each other. After all, in a conspiracy game, what is an ally except an enemy who has not yet shown his stripes?
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb120\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f184\fs34\insrsid6771226 12.6 Sample Organizations
\par }{\b\i\f184\insrsid6771226 The Amazing Vinka\rquote s }{\b\i\f184\insrsid5639858 Traveling}{\b\i\f184\insrsid6771226  Circus
